><span class=title> If.. then</span><hr size=1> How would I structure an 'If... then' type of question.  And what words would be used?  For example, how would you say, &quot;If you aren't coming tomorrow, let me know&quot;?  Or something like that.  Help me. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ueneref.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eneref</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/19/01 9:12:49 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: If.. then</span><hr size=1> How much do you know of Japanese grammar....<br>
<br>
These structures are called 'conditionals'.... meaning, there's a condition upon which something happens....<br>
<br>
This case uses perfective distal style and hacks it up....<br>
<br>
It's always:<br>
<br>
if X, then Y<br>
<br>
So... in this case, you would say:<br>
<br>
If you're not coming tomorrow, let me know.<br>
<br>
NOT...<br>
<br>
let me know if you're not coming tomorrow...<br>
<br>
<br>
You're not coming tomorrow:<br>
<br>
(this is verbose)<br>
Ashita anata ha kimasen.<br>
<br>
Let me know:<br>
<br>
Oshiete kudasai.<br>
<br>
To put these together, we use the perfective direct style of 'to not come' --  konakatta (changes from kuru to konai -- irregular japanese verb) and add -ra<br>
<br>
Which becomes:<br>
<br>
Ashita anata ha konakattara, oshiete kudasai.<br>
<br>
In most cases, you don't want to use anata if you can avoid it... it's a little rude....<br>
<br>
Omae works as a replacement... but in Japanese, which is very situational and contextual, you can usually drop that...<br>
<br>
Ashita konakattara, oshiete (kudasai).<br>
<br>
<br>
Same rules apply to other verbs...<br>
<br>
Drink -- nomu  -- nonda  -- nondara<br>
Eat -- teberu -- tabeta -- tabetara<br>
Buy -- kau -- katta  -- kattara<br>
<br>
e.g.<br>
<br>
If I buy this pen, I will write a letter....  (okay, stupid example, but I'm not very good at these)<br>
<br>
Watashi ha kono pen wo kattara, tegami wo kaku. <br>
<br>
etc, etc...<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=superflat>superflat</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/27/01 12:45:35 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: If.. then</span><hr size=1> I just want to add a little (actually alot) to what Eneref said.<br>
<br>
Conditionals in Japanese are considerably more nuanced than they are in English (at least it seems that way to me), and so there is more than one way to get an &quot;if then&quot; type statement.  Here are a couple:<br>
<br>
The one Eneref used exclusively in his reply was tara form.  It is contructed by taking the verb putting it in plain past and then adding ra to the end of it, as was explained.  This form does indicate the &quot;if A, then B&quot; idea but is used mostly in cases where A and B have already occured, or when you are hypothesizing that they will occur.<br>
<br>
In times when the connection between A and B is more certain you can use &quot;to&quot;.  &quot;Whenever A, then B&quot; would be &quot;A to B&quot;.  For example:<br>
<br>
ichinichi e wo kaite, kaite bakkari to kakenakunaru yo!<br>
whenever I just draw all day long, I become unable to draw!<br>
<br>
Similary, &quot;if A then B&quot; is a general, elemental relationship or the will or wish of the speaker, you can use ba form.  Making ba form is a little complicated (well not really, but this is already too long so...) so I think I'll leave up to you to look up, if your interested.  Here are a couple of example's:<br>
<br>
Chicago deha, nigatsu ni nareba hijou ni samukunarimasu<br>
In Chicago, when February comes, it gets really cold.<br>
<br>
kyoumi ga areba, shiraberubeki desu<br>
If you're interested, you should look it up.<br>
<br>
For hypotheticals you can use nara.  Like &quot;to&quot; all you have to do is stick nara between the two sentences:<br>
<br>
manga wo takusan yomu nara, nihongo wo benkyoushita hou ga ii<br>
if you (plan to) read a lot of manga, you should learn Japanese (before reading it).<br>
<br>
Sorry about the overkill.  I hope it helps<br>
<br>
